hm i hate to say it but moving to doctrine might require a different solution for oracle.
first i had to unset the port in `lib/db.php` or doctrine will create a non working connection string:
```php
			case 'oci':
					$connectionparams = array(
							'user' => $user,
							'password' => $pass,
							'host' => $host,
							'port' => $port,
							'dbname' => $name,
							'charset' => 'al32utf8',
							'driver' => 'oci8',
					);
					if (!$port) {
						unset ($connectionparams['port']);
					}
					break;
```
 after hacking around the oracle limitations that clob columns cannot be used in where clauses:
in `lib/app.php` getenabledapps():
```php

	/**
	 * get all enabled apps
	 */
	public static function getenabledapps() {
		if(!oc_config::getvalue('installed', false)) {
			return array();
		}
		$apps=array('files');
		if (oc_config::getvalue('dbtype', false) === 'oci') {
			//fixme: hack to use clob column in where clause
			$query = 'select `appid` from `*prefix*appconfig`'
				.' where `configkey` = \'enabled\' and to_char(`configvalue`)=\'yes\'';
		} else {
			$query = 'select `appid` from `*prefix*appconfig`'
				.' where `configkey` = \'enabled\' and `configvalue`=\'yes\'';
		}
		$stmt = oc_db::prepare( $query );
		[...]
```
and `lib/user.php` isenabled():
```php

	/**
	 * checks if a user is enabled
	 * @param string $userid
	 * @return bool
	 */
	public static function isenabled($userid) {
		if (oc_config::getvalue('dbtype', false) === 'oci') {
			//fixme: hack to use clob column in where clause
			$query = 'select `userid` from `*prefix*preferences`'
				.' where `userid` = ? and `appid` = ? and `configkey` = ? and to_char(`configvalue`) = ?';
		} else {
			$query = 'select `userid` from `*prefix*preferences`'
				.' where `userid` = ? and `appid` = ? and `configkey` = ? and `configvalue` = ?';
		}
		$stmt = oc_db::prepare($query);
		[...]
```

someone also forgot to escape the displayname in `lib/user/database.php` getdisplayname():
```php
	public function getdisplayname($uid) {
		if( $this->userexists($uid) ) {
			$query = oc_db::prepare( 'select `displayname` from `*prefix*users` where `uid` = ?' );
```
now i ran into the above issue with null values in the path column, so i removed it from the db_structure.xml, increased the version number in util.php and now stumbled over this:

```
an exception occurred while executing 'alter table oc_appconfig add (appid varchar2(32) default '' not null, configkey varchar2(64) default '' not null, configvalue clob not null)': ora-00942: table or view does not exist
```

this means schema evolution will break for oracle when moving to doctrine.

@bartv2 i can commit my fixes to this branch but i am at a loss how to deal with the db migration issue. the doctrine developers don't think its a good idea to escape everything, and i agree, but it was the only solution i saw to avoid having to check whether every column identifier is a reserved keyword in one of the supported rdsms or not. to be honest i'd love to get rid of the backtick mess i introduced. but then we will need to find another way to make sure that no column matches a reserved word ... the other solution would be to somehow make doctrine correctly quote identifiers when doing schema migration ... something i don't think is a viable solution.

the upside of moving to non quoted queries would be that it is a lot easier to have jenkins barf when he finds quotes in $sql queries than have him barf when he does not find backticks. this comes at the cost of developers having to keep in mind reserved keywords, such as 'user' or 'group' ... an lots of others. but that's what the doctine guys recommend: http://www.doctrine-project.org/jira/browse/dbal-40 in that discussion there is even one of the mdb2 developers who says quoting everything is a bad idea. i tend to follow their opinion ... because ... duh ... they know databases and stuff ...

@deepdiver1975 @icewind1991 @karlitschek @tanghus opinions?
